John Edward: Language skills are of great importance to the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools have an academic success story. In 2018, this success was sustained by outstanding test results supported by sports, arts, music and other civil society studies.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland and represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), these schools work to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their later education and higher education, their chosen career, and to become world citizens.
As educational institutions that can prepare a specific curriculum for students and apply it, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and necessary course in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “When you talk to someone in a language they understand,
If you speak the language of your heart, you speak the language of your heart.”
If we want to build relationships with people from other countries and build mutual trust, this is a strong reminder that we should not rely solely on English.
Based on this year’s final exam results, we can see that language lessons in independent schools are at the top of the score sheets with the highest passing grades.
This year, 68% of students taking foreign language courses completed their courses with a high score of A.
According to data collected from 74 member schools of SCIS, 72 percent of students taking Chinese courses, 72 percent of German courses, 69 percent of French courses and 63 percent of Spanish courses passed A.
This data shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign language lessons as basic skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Language courses, which are elective courses, are now equivalent to FeTeMM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics) courses in the curricula of independent schools and other schools.
A study conducted in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of the reasons employers suffer when hiring new employees for vacancies are related to a lack of language skills.
For this reason, language skills are becoming more and more imperative in preparing young people for their future careers.
These skills have become key skills in a globalized world as more employers require language proficiency for possible job opportunities.
If the person knows a second language, regardless of the career he chooses, he will have a real advantage in the future because he has this ability to use it for the rest of his life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov, 75% of the more than 4,000 people living in the UK don’t know enough foreign languages to chat, and in no foreign language except French (15%), the ratio of speakers doesn’t reach a two-digit number.
Therefore, investing in language learning today is of great importance for children of the future.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially the languages of emerging economies, will increase children’s chances of finding a suitable and reasonable job in the future.
The languages taught in schools in Scotland are different.
While certain schools offer more traditional modern language options, some schools also teach languages that are thought to be important for the UK in 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
No matter what field your child is interested in, they may choose one of the various foreign language options taught by specialist teachers in independent schools.
Scottish independent schools aim to provide a teaching environment that will prepare children for the future and equip them with the skills needed for success.
It is an undeniable fact that foreign languages continue to be vital for the future of the country in today’s global business environment. This should also be reflected in real educational life.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and success to Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools
