North Korea says unilateral disarmament without confidence is "in no way"
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the country's ongoing embargoes have deepened its distrust of the United States and under these circumstances the country cannot unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the world organization's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear testing site, and promising not to produce nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“Despite this, we do not see any reward from the United States,” he added.
“Without any confidence in the United States, we will not be able to believe in our own national security, and under these circumstances there will be no way that we can unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri reiterates his familiar North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "stageless" approach to which North Korea will be rewarded for its gradual steps, his statements seem important, as he did not unilaterally hand over the lifting of nuclear weapons, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri cited joint statements by Donald Trump and Kim Jong Un at a summit in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work on "de-nuclearization of the Korean peninsula" between the U.S. president and a North Korean leader for the first time.
North Korea is looking for ways to officially end the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to loosen tough international sanctions in North Korea.
"The United States first insists on 'nuclear disarmament' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goals in a compelling way. It even opposes 'reporting the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is the empty imagination of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions reinforce our insecurities.”
Ri made no hints about a second summit plan between U.S. President Trump and Kim, which was highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If South Korea and not the United States were dealing with this nuclear disarmament issue, the issue of disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not be such a blind node."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was quite different from last year’s speech by “Mr. Demon President” Trump at the UN General Assembly last year, when he said it was inevitable for North Korea’s rockets to target the US mainland after calling Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to "completely annihilate" North Korea last year, praised Kim in the United Nations this year for his courage to take steps on disarmament, but said there was still much work to be done and that the sanctions should continue until North Korea is cleared of nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said, “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years, or five months.”
China and Russia have claimed that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council’s sanctions must continue vigorously and without any failures until a complete, definitive and verified nuclear disarmament is carried out.”
The Security Council unanimously increased North Korea's sanctions since 2006 in an effort to stop funding Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri during the UN General Assembly, then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Hours after leaving Pyongyang in July, North Korea condemned him for "mafia claims".
During a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States takes “reciprocal measures.”
Moon said the “reciprocal measures” Kim was looking for were Trump’s security guarantees in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year leads all of its students to sleep more in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of ‘all-nighters’ working through caffeine.
One academic found that when it comes to taking care of themselves, the students of the world’s number one university are unaware of even the most basic information.
The course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S., was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep therapy at Harvard Medical School and expert at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
The lesson was inspired by a speech he made about the impact of sleep deprivation on his ability to learn.
“At the end of the conversation, a female student came to me and said, ‘Why is all this being said to me now, when I’m in my final year?’
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me.”
The course, which opens for the first time this year, explains the basics of how good sleep habits help students achieve academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of health services at the university, said the university decided to open the course after realizing that students were seriously sleepless during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One section contains a picture of a dorm room where students listen to coffee cups, curtains, instructors, and books by clicking on the effects of coffee and light, as well as how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as what is being told about the importance of regular sleep.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their own daily routine.
“We know that it won’t change students’ behavior instantly.
However, we believe that if you have the right to learn how smoking affects your health, you have the right to learn the same,” Czeisler added.
Adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students, i.e. sleep deprivation, is a growing problem, the culture of being proud to “work all night” still exists.
Getting enough sleep and ensuring that sleep is of good quality should be a "secret weapon" for students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety. Even to avoid gaining excess weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, causing students to feel constantly hungry, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemical and physical biology, received a course from Professor Czeisler in his first year at school last year, and helped Professor Czeisler design the course.
She said the course opened her eyes and inspired her to create awareness across the campus.
In the next step, she hopes to ask her graduate students to complete a similar course before joining competitive institutions.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for the time they wake up, as well as the time they sleep. He also warns them about the harmful effects of "blue light", which disrupts the daily rhythm emitted by electronic displays and LED lights, causing sleep problems.
