New cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to "see" malicious cells
New cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to "see" and kill malicious cells
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malicious cells as part of treatment
The method involves taking immune cells from patients and modifying them in the lab.
These cells can "see" and re-inject the protein that is common in many cancer cells
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with varying levels of cancer.
A woman who was treated with a vaccine that taught the immune system to recognize malicious cells saw uterine cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
