Speaking to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country has improved.
"Thanks to the fight against terrorism, the ground is now more solid and our lands are safer," he said.
The government is continuing its rehabilitation process to restore the areas destroyed by terrorists to normal.
Unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods, and due to terrorism, there are all the conditions for migrants to voluntarily return to the countries where they have been forced to leave.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country as a result of the war that began in 2011.
Of the people still living in the country, six million are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime was open to future aid to rebuild the devastated country.
But he underlined that they would not accept conditional aid and aid from rebel-sponsored countries.
