Red Tide News: Groups in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are shrinking
A recent report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in Red Tide groups in some parts of the Tampa Bay area.
Inappropriate reproduction conditions are reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier regions, according to the FWC, which explains the shrinking groups.
During a period of reproduction, the Red Tide expands 130 miles from North Pinellas to the South Lee region.
Smaller groups can be found within 10 miles of the Hillsborough District, but fewer than last week.
The red tide has also been observed in the Pasco region.
Last week, medium-sized groups were observed offshore and offshore in the Pinellas Region, small and large groups outside the Hillsborough Region, certain ambiguous and large groups in the Manatee Region, certain ambiguous and large groups on the coast and outshore in the Sarasota Region, certain ambiguous and medium-sized groups in the Charlotte Region, certain ambiguous and large groups in the Collier and small outshore of the Lee Region.
Respiratory disorders continue to be reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier regions.
